  "doc_id": "5611",
  "text": "In the model a supervisory policy is necessary to avoid excessive risk taking by a banker and to provide her with incentives to exert effort monitoring her bank's loans. A supervisory policy characterized by a minimum capital requirement and a licensing-closure rule will work. However, the government (even if it seeks to maximize social welfare) is unable to credibly commit to this supervisory policy. As in [CITATION_1] , the government confronts a dynamic commitment problem that makes non-credible its policy. As a consequence, the banker will take excessive risks. This provides a rationale for hiring an independent bank supervisor.",
